'''Euphoric recall''' is a psychological term for the tendency of people to remember past experiences in a positive light, while overlooking negative experiences associated with that event(s). Euphoric recall has been cited as a factor in [[substance dependence]],<ref name="Perkinson2011">{{cite book|last=Perkinson|first=Robert R.|title=Chemical Dependency Counseling: A Practical Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kpYzKIWOVZIC&pg=PA107|date=2011-06-17|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=9781412979214|pages=107–108}}</ref><ref name="Keane2002">{{cite book|last=Keane|first=Helen|title=What's Wrong with Addiction?|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QqZsDnXS3-cC&pg=PA78|year=2002|publisher=Melbourne University Publish|isbn=9780522849912|page=78}}</ref><ref name="WashtonZweben2009">{{cite book|last1=Washton|first1=Arnold M.|last2=Zweben|first2=Joan E.|title=Cocaine & Methamphetamine Addiction: Treatment, Recovery, and Relapse Prevention|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dT30MvJxsdIC&pg=PA170|year=2009|publisher=W. W. Norton|isbn=9780393703023|pages=170–}}</ref> as well as [[anger problems]].<ref name="Fleeman2003">{{cite book|last=Fleeman|first=William|title=The Pathways to Peace Anger Management Workbook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2zSgqdZzHhIC&pg=PA87|year=2003|publisher=Hunter House|isbn=9780897934176|pages=87–88}}</ref> Individuals may become obsessed with recreating the remembered pleasures of the past.<ref name="Daley1988">{{cite book|last=Daley|first=Dennis C.|title=Relapse: Conceptual, Research, and Clinical Perspectives|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i9L0vFM-qSoC&pg=PA153|year=1988|publisher=Haworth Press|isbn=9780866569194|pages=153–171}}</ref>
