In mathematics, '''polyad''' is a concept of [[category theory]] introduced by [[Jean Bénabou]] in generalising [[monad (category theory)|monad]]s.<ref>{{Citation|last=Benabou|first=Jean|year=1967|title=Introduction to Bicategories}}</ref> A '''polyad''' in a [[bicategory]] ''D'' is a bicategory morphism ''Φ'' from a locally punctual bicategory ''C'' to ''D'', {{nowrap|''&Phi;'' : ''C'' → ''D''}}. (A bicategory ''C'' is called locally punctual if all hom-categories ''C''(''X'',''Y'') consist of one object and one morphism only.) Monads are polyads {{nowrap|''&Phi;'' : ''C'' → ''D''}} where ''C'' has only one object.

